text: hi everyone joey macaroni here the
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new benny the
butcher album tana talk 4. buffalo
rapper griselda records own benny the
butcher brand new project here it is the
latest installment in his fan favorite
tana talk series which is an interesting
calling back to my roots type move
especially considering his last record
in 2020 burden of proof which was a
pretty successful attempt for benny at
making a project that was a little more
commercially and industry friendly with
big features from the likes of rick ross
and lil wayne cleaner production guys
like hit boy in the mix but tana talk 4
by comparison brings more of what
exactly put benny on the map with loads
of cerebral production from the
alchemist as well as stuff that has more
boom bap leanings from derringer this
record is purely benny in the thick of
his comfort zone and he couldn't sound
better in this position but by that same
token this move is a little deceiving
because rap fans are pretty well
acquainted with what griselda and benny
have to offer at this point and tana
talk 4 doesn't exactly expand benny's
cocaine vocabulary the record is also a
pretty standard length and starts and
ends somewhat unceremoniously but damn
if it's not still packed with highlights
like 10 more commandments which is a
conceptual sequel to biggie's legendary
10 crack commandments i have to admit it
takes balls for benny to even flirt with
doing a song like this but i suppose
diddy is on the track as well and you
couldn't get a more sound endorsement
than that benny's flows and lyricism are
of course up to snuff but what's more
important is he actually adds
10 more reasonable commandments to
biggie's original verses like getting
out of the game as soon as you can and
no posting and clout chasing on social
media with what you do the song is so
good it's a serious achievement but
there are more highlights to come that
focus mostly on benny like super plug
where he goes over his past experiences
and motivations as a drug dealer
describes catching cases the paranoia
that he feels also lengthy road trips to
go pick up product set to a seriously
cinematic beat with lots of sound play
from the alchemist the way benny's bars
and owls beat hear pairs it comes
together in a way where i can just
instantly visualize everything that he's
saying like uh scene to scene zoe's
revenge sports a mesmerizing alchemist
b2 the steady rhythms and distant horn
melodies are great i also love the way
we get these warm hits of orchestrations
that seep into the mix very subtly it's
a warm backdrop for benny to reminisce
over about how he hustled his way to
where he is now but also the structure
of this track too the verses the
pre-choruses the refrains benny has like
really upped his hook game here there's
also a great series of features that
really make this project too like johnny
p's caddy with j cole where benny opens
up the entire lp painting a lyrical
picture of his skills his and griselda's
growth in the music industry and the
mental scars left on him by a life of
dealing it's an absolutely cold
performance placed on top of this
nostalgic set of easygoing beets and
dreamy vocal chops and j cole
essentially complements the vibe with a
lot of gritty lyricism some skillful
brags but also hilarious jabs of his
reputation like this one bar about going
to hell if jesus asked him for a feature
out of fear that either he would go too
far with it or you know just the rarity
with which he gives features or allows
features on his own projects there's
also weekends in the parries with bowley
james which sports some killer drumless
production which is becoming more and
more in style these days and for benny i
feel like this kind of beat is perfect
because it puts more weight on his words
on his lyricism i think you have to be
kind of cut from a special cloth to
carry a drumless beat especially with
this pressure from his pen line i'm
loving that one also given his low
low-key delivery and the lyrical themes
that are often found in his music and
his multiple connections to the
alchemist is there a better fit on this
song than bully of of course not which
just goes to show how much thought benny
is putting into who is going where on
this record because there's not a single
feature or appearance that doesn't seem
super appropriate so of course there was
going to be chemistry with conway on
tyson versus ali which is a really smart
cut about standing out artistically
playing the long game in music as well
while others are kind of fading out
after their 15 minutes of fame benny
dealing with criticisms and comparisons
to other artists it's a solid piece of
lyrical meta commentary from him
meanwhile conway shows up with a verse
that is uh very encouraging it's like a
pat on benny's back like hey you're
doing great i'm so proud we have history
this is amazing more and more these days
when i see a conway track or i hear a
conway feature i look forward to what
genuine emotion he's going to be getting
across whether that's anger
introspection or even here admiration
deeper into the lp we also have some
really solid trades with 38 speci on
uncle bun where you can find these guys
building on each other's flows and rhyme
schemes for a few bars after each other
there's a chilling beat on this one
which is killer i love benny's lines
that are in reference to bun b but man
38 sounds absolutely insane on this
track like dude switch so i don't talk
to people two clips that's enough for
you and your alter ego but like that's
one of many sick lines across the track
that i could just spend you know minutes
upon minutes diving in so look coming
away from this lp uh it doesn't come
together as any huge like great flowing
concept or well groomed project or
anything like that in fact i would say
there are a few cuts here that are a
little average for benny like the stove
got cook's track for example which i
thought had a great beat but the chorus
is super tangled and long-winded not to
mention he sort of ends the track off in
a way that feels a little abrupt and
half-baked i ran into a lot of the same
issues with guerrero featuring westside
gunn who also i think
brings the heat down as he finishes the
second half of the song off the only
thing i think i really loved about this
cut was the beat then mr chow hall i
thought was just an alright closer feels
almost like a journal entry set to a
creepy key loop from a horror movie
soundtrack a real coke epilogue with
benny also updating us on his current
mindset in regards to
his fame and success griselda's fame and
success generally navigating a predatory
music industry where he's trying to
maintain artistic freedom i get that but
the whole track isn't really well
structured or built out in any way it
just kind of seems like some fleeting
final thoughts not so much a summation
or a grand finale as much as it is a
sort of a to be continued that followed
after a series of loosely affiliated
short stories vignettes or song concepts
but with that being said most of the
songs here i thought personally were
some of benny's best to date from this
point when we have discussions of why
benny the butcher is so good our mind
should go to tracks like super plug and
10 more commandments so yeah overall i
thought this project was really good
certainly one of benny's best and it
shows that continuing to refine what you
already do so well is a valid path to
success feeling a strong 7 to a light 8
